(44, 13, 24, 41, 1, 2, 8, 'the baptism of repentance', 'Connection of John the Baptist', 'Both passages emphasize John’s role in preaching the baptism of repentance. Acts 13:24 mentions his preaching to Israel, while Mark 1:4 describes his baptism in the wilderness for the remission of sins.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 24, 42, 3, 2, 20, 'the baptism of repentance', 'John''s Baptism of Repentance', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of baptism of repentance, highlighting John''s role in preparing the way for the Lord. Acts 13:24 refers to John''s preaching, which is elaborated in Luke 3:2-20, detailing his message and actions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 24, 44, 10, 37, 37, NULL, 'Connection of John''s Baptism', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the baptism which John preached, linking his ministry to the broader narrative of Jesus'' coming. This connection highlights the role of John in preparing the way for Jesus in the context of repentance.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 24, 42, 1, 76, 76, 'the baptism of repentance', 'Connection of Prophetic Preparation', 'Both passages emphasize the role of a prophet preparing the way for the Lord. John the Baptist''s preaching of repentance aligns with the prophetic mission described in Luke.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 24, 43, 1, 6, 8, 'baptism of repentance', 'Connection of John the Baptist''s Role', 'Both passages emphasize John’s role in preparing for Jesus. Acts highlights his preaching of repentance, while John focuses on his witness to the Light.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 25, 40, 3, 11, 11, NULL, 'Connection Between John the Baptist''s Statements', 'Both passages emphasize the humility of John the Baptist in relation to the one who comes after him. They highlight that John is not worthy to untie the shoes of this mightier figure, indicating his subordinate role.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 25, 41, 1, 7, 7, 'whose shoes of his feet I am not worthy to loose', 'Connection of John the Baptist''s Message', 'Both passages emphasize the coming of one mightier than John. They share the phrase about being unworthy to loose the shoes of this figure, highlighting John''s humility.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 25, 43, 1, 26, 27, 'whose shoes of his feet I am not worthy to loose', 'John''s Humility and Precedence', 'Both passages emphasize John the Baptist''s acknowledgment of someone greater coming after him. They share the phrase about being unworthy to unloose the shoes of this figure, highlighting John''s humility.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 25, 42, 3, 15, 16, 'whose shoes of his feet I am not worthy to loose', 'Connection Between John the Baptist''s Role', 'Both passages emphasize John''s acknowledgment of his subordinate role to the one coming after him. They highlight his unworthiness to unloose the latchet of the shoes of this mightier figure.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 25, 43, 1, 20, 23, 'I am not he', 'John the Baptist''s Identity', 'Both passages emphasize John the Baptist''s denial of being the Christ and his role as a forerunner. In Acts, he states he is not worthy to loose the shoes of the one coming after him, while in John, he identifies himself as ''the voice of one crying in the wilderness.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 25, 44, 20, 24, 24, NULL, 'Connection of Finishing Courses', 'This connection highlights the theme of fulfilling one''s course in ministry. Both passages emphasize the importance of completing the mission given by God, with John acknowledging his role and Paul expressing his commitment to finish his course.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 25, 41, 6, 16, 28, 'I am not he', 'Connection Between John and Herod', 'Both passages emphasize John the Baptist''s fate and his role as a prophet. In Acts, John acknowledges the one coming after him, while in Mark, Herod reflects on John''s beheading, indicating his significance and the consequences of his prophetic message.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
